title: Top 5 Districts of Residence for Afghans in Pakistan, Pakistan, 2005
name: Top 5 Districts of Residence for Afghans in Pakistan, Pakistan, 2005
description:
Top 5 Districts of Residence in Pakistan

Afghans in Pakistan are concentrated near their country of origin, with nearly 87 percent residing in
the two Pakistani provinces bordering Afghanistan; North West Frontier Province (NWFP) and
Balochistan. Because the population of Pakistan is concentrated in the provinces of Punjab and
Sindh, the Afghan population has a disproportionate impact in the border provinces. If population
ratios in Pakistan provinces have not changed since the 1998 national census, Afghans in Punjab
would constitute a mere 0.24 percent of the Pakistani population, but in Balochistan would be
equivalent to 10 percent of the Pakistanis. In NWFP, Afghans would equal 7.6 percent of the
Pakistani population. In particular districts, Afghans would form an even higher portion of the total
population. This uneven distribution makes their presence, and both negative and positive effects,
much more visible to the Pakistani population in particular areas.
The census also shows the presence of larger families among Afghans in Balochistan, with each
family averaging 6.7 people. In contrast, NWFP, host to most of the Afghans, shows an average
family size of 5.3 people. The overall average of 5.6 people per family is a marked fall from 6.3,
which was considered the family size norm for Afghans in Pakistan by studies carried out in the
1980s
The Afghan presence in Sindh, mainly concentrated in Karachi, has reduced markedly because of
repatriation over the past three years. Afghans now form a relatively small part of the urban
population that has been estimated at some 14 million people.
